    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="241"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d241">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">714.44A15/237</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Welles</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the British Ambassador</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Halifax</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-18">May 18,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Lord Halifax</hi>: With reference to our
                    conversation of yesterday in which I once more expressed the hope of this
                    Government <pb facs="0219" n="209" xml:id="pg_209"/> that some appropriate and
                    early way might be found by the Government of Great Britain to further a
                    friendly and equitable adjustment of the question which has arisen involving the
                    boundary between British Honduras and the Republic of Guatemala, I am enclosing
                    herewith a paraphrase of a telegram<note n="5" xml:id="d241fn1">Telegram No. 69,
                        May 17, noon, <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                    </note> I have received this morning from the American Minister in Guatemala
                    City. I believe that you will find this message to be of interest.</p>
                <p>I feel I should once more express my fear that so long as this dispute continues,
                    it affords a very favorable opportunity for the agents of powers now at war with
                    Great Britain, and unfriendly to the United States, to conduct propaganda, not
                    only in Guatemala but in Mexico as well, which propaganda has already assumed
                    considerable proportions and may at any moment assume a dangerous aspect.</p>
                <p>Believe me</p>
                <p>Yours very sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sumner Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
